[2] Indonesia (Central Java)
Date: Sun 9 Dec 2007
Source: Jawa Pos [in Indonesian, trans., edited]
<http://www.jawapos.co.id/index.php?act=detail_radar&id=184467&c=109>


The spread of dengue fever in Jombang is increasingly worrying. As of
yesterday [8 Dec 2007], 537 [dengue fever] sufferers were given
intensive treatment in the Community Health Centre and the Hospital
in Jombang. Moreover, emergency status was given due to the increase
in dengue fever cases.

This case figure is more than twice that compared with last year
(2006), so a further increase must be guarded against, said the
Jombang head of Health Service, Dr. Andhy Bhinuko.

Moreover, the level of spread of the illness, which is caused by the
bite of [dengue virus carrying-] _Aedes aegypti_, has not stopped
throughout 2007. Usually in the period from May up to August no
[dengue] cases occur.

The increase in [dengue] cases became more apparent starting in
October [2007] when 21 sufferers were treated. In the following
month, November, the number jumped to 44 cases with the death of 2
people. The total dengue fever [2007] case load up to this December
was 537 people with 16 deaths.

The location where dengue has been spreading includes the Jombang
Subdistrict, Diwek and the Mojowarno Subdistrict. Areas at risk
include the Kudu Subdistrict, Jogoroto, Mojoagung and the Peterongan
Subdistrict.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A Jawa Pos article published 4 Dec 2007
(<http://www.jawapos.co.id/index.php?act=detail_radar&id=183560&c=109>)
indicated that dengue virus transmission now occurs year around, and
not just during the rainy season. - Mod.TY]

******
[3] Indonesia (East Java)
Date: Mon 3 Dec 2007
Source: Jawa Pos [in Indonesian, trans. & summ., edited]
<http://www.jawapos.co.id/index.php?act=detail_radar&id=183489&c=91>


The Health Service indicated that the Bondowoso Regency responded to
the serious dengue fever epidemic in the Dadapan Village, Kecamatan
Grujugan after dozens of villagers underwent the intensive treatment
in the Daerah Hospital.

Fumigation was carried out by the officials and the Grujugan
Community Health Centre, not only outside the area [but also in] the
residents' houses. The fumigation was done to kill _Aedes aegypti_
mosquitoes that spread the dengue fever illness.

In addition to fumigation, powdered abate was distributed to
residents to kill larval _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[4] Indonesia (East Kalimantan)
Date: Wed 5 Dec 2007
Source: Kompas [in Indonesian, trans. & summ., edited]
<http://www.kompas.com/ver1/Nusantara/0712/05/092501.htm>


During the Period January-November 2007, as many as 89 East
Kalimantan residents died from dengue fever. The number has increased
compared to last year [2006] which totaled 80 people from January to
December, said the Head of the East Kalimantan Health Section,
Sutarnyoto, in the office of East Kalimantan Governor, Samarinda, on
Wednesday (5 Dec [2007]). This is worrying, he stressed.

This year, 4276 people were infected by dengue fever; whereas, last
year [2006], according to Sutarnyoto, 2838 people were infected by
dengue fever.

--
Communicatd by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[East Kalimantan, Indonesia, is located on the SE part of Borneo
Island and an interactive ProMED health map of this area can be accessed at:
