[7] Pakistan (Rawalpindi)
Date: Tue 4 Dec 2007
Source: Daily Times
<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C12%5C04%5Cstory_4-12-2007_pg11_4>


Two more suspected dengue fever patients were on Monday [3 Dec
2007] admitted to Rawalpindi General Hospital (RGH), raising the
number of suspected cases to 5. Doctors said the 5 infected
people, kept in quarantine, had visited Karachi and Peshawar and were
diagnosed with high fever, vomiting and shivering which were
symptomatic of dengue fever.

They said if proper measures like fumigation and spray of
insecticides were not taken immediately, the infection could assume
[epidemic] proportions.

Dr. Fayyaz Ahmad, Assistant Medical Superintendent (Administration),
told the Daily Times that blood samples of the [dengue] suspected
patients were taken and sent to the National Institute of Health
(NIH) for dengue serology on Monday [3 Dec 2007].

He said reports of 3 patients already admitted to the hospital had
been received, one of which was positive [for dengue antibody? -
Mod.TY]. He said the patient had been put in an isolated ward. The
hospital's private ward has been declared as an isolated ward and all
the 5 patients are being treated there.

Doctors took blood samples [from one patient] and sent them to the
NIH for diagnosis of both Congo [Crimean hemorrhagic fever] and dengue fever.

[Byline: Aamir Yasin]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[It would be important to know if some of these patients are infected
with CCHF virus, which would pose a risk to hospital personnel & which
would require isolation, and dengue viruses, which would not. ProMED
would be interested to know if any of these turn out to be CCHF
patients.

Fumigation mentioned in this report would kill adult _Aedes_ dengue
vector mosquitoes, but halting or slowing of an epidemic would be
temporary. Without elimination of larval breeding sites, a new
generation of vector mosquitoes would soon emerge and virus
transmission would resume. - Mod.TY]

******
[8] Brazil (Ceara)
Date: Sat 8 Dec 2007
Source: O Povo [in Portuguese, trans & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
<http://www.opovo.com.br/opovo/fortaleza/750869.html>

The Secretary of Health for the state of Ceara (SESA) confirmed the
10th DHF death this year [2007] in the state, the latest in
Fortaleza. According to the weekly dengue bulletin published by SESA,
[dengue] deaths have been confirmed in Sobral (3 [deaths]), Juazeiro
del Norte (2), Caucaia (1), Salitre (1), Quixada (1) and Camocim (1).

Of an additional [27] suspected DHF deaths being investigated, 16 have
been registered in Fortaleza. The others occurred in Amontada (1),
Caninde (1), Caucaia (2), Itapipoca (2), Maracanau (2), Pacajus (1),
Taua (1) & Tejucuoca (1).

This year [2007] there has been notification of 631 DHF cases, of
which 284 have been [laboratory? Mod. TY] confirmed. This is the
greatest number of cases since 2003, when 291 cases were documented.
Up to the present [in 2007], 40 255 cases of classical dengue fever
have been registered in 182 of Ceara's 184 municipalities. Of these,
23 595 have been confirmed in 166 municipalities. The 1st dengue case
in Ceara occurred in 1986.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The state of Ceara has been living with dengue for 10 years, and
unhappily the number of deaths has tended to increase. - Mod.LJS]

[It would be helpful to know if the case fatality rate has increased,
perhaps due to increased virus virulence or to problems with medical
management of DHF cases, or if there have been an increasing number
of DHF cases in the state. - Mod.TY]

[An interactive ProMED health map of Brazil showing the location of
states and cities including Ceara and Forteleza on the central
Atlantic coast, can be accessed at:
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=-10.8,-53.1,4>. - Mod.TY]

