[9] Brazil (Sao Paulo state)
Date: Sat 08 Dec 2007
Source: Cosmo On Line [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
<http://www.cosmo.com.br/cidades/campinas/integra.asp?id=214339>


Dengue [virus] transmission, which had a rapid interruption in
October [2007], returned to hit Campinas. Over 20 cases have been
confirmed in 2 dozen neighborhoods.

"The situation is really worrisome, mainly because many of these
localities [having dengue cases] are slum areas, with poor sanitary
conditions and many [mosquito] breeding sites, which facilitate an
explosion of [dengue] cases", said the municipal coordinator of
dengue control actions, Andreia Von Zuben.

According to her, the confirmed cases in November [2007] are isolated
[instances] of [dengue] transmission, but indicate theat the [vector]
mosquito is proliferating with or without dry spells or the
intensification of rains. The total numbers of dengue cases confirmed
serologically this year [2007] in Campinas is 5050. However, the
Office of Health Surveillance expects that there will be 13 000
[dengue] cases with 8000 serologically confirmed.

Andreia explained that an explosion of [dengue] cases are expected
this summer, and will [result in] implementation of "focal blockades."

The focal blockade consists of triggering all the control actions
within an area of 300 meters around the building where the confirmed
case occurred. This includes elimination of [mosquito] breeding sites
and treating [others] with biological larvicides (BTI [_Bacillus
thurengiensis_ serovar _israelensis_. - Mod.TY] in areas of water
accumulation which can not be removed. "BTI does not pose any danger
to human health in the elimination of mosquito larvae," she said.

Other blockade measures include fogging with insecticides, treatment
with larvacides at points of risk such as [vehicle] tire and scrap
metal yards; proactive new suspected case detection, and
investigation of [areas of] all cases in order to identify mosquito
breeding sites.

--
